      "date": "2022-01-06 21:57:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI checked the ticket and I do not see what harm is there?\n\nThe useful purpose of those messages is also to show that calls into other functions from inside of these functions are done from these functions.\n\nAnd it's not like we run with this debug by default so I'd like to better understand the problem here",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a201ff18ee8e2cb80c32a38cdd4df45dc1763965",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2022-01-21 06:55:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> I checked the ticket and I do not see what harm is there?\n > \n > The useful purpose of those messages is also to show that calls\n > into other functions from inside of these functions are done from\n > these functions.\n > \n > And it's not like we run with this debug by default so I'd like to\n > better understand the problem here\n\nOleg, when I was debugging another problem, these messages were filling the debug logs.  They don't provide any useful information about the connection, the messages being sent, etc. so there is no way to match them against any other part of the code.  I don't think they really provide any benefit at all.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
